HISTORY

The Ford Mustang is an American carmanufactured by Ford. It was originally based on the platform of the second generation North American Ford Falcon, a compact car. The original 1962 Ford Mustang I two-seater concept car had evolved into the 1963 Mustang II four-seater concept car which Ford used to pretest how the public would take interest in the first production Mustang. The 1963 Mustang II concept car was designed with a variation of the production model's front and rear ends with a roof that was 2.7 inches shorter. Introduced early on April 17, 1964 (16 days after the Plymouth Barracuda), and thus dubbed as a "1964½" by Mustang fans, the 1965 Mustang was the automaker's most successful launch since the Model A. The Mustang has undergone several transformations to its current sixth generation. SOURCE:  WIKIPEDIA

CLASSIC CAR RESTORATIONS:

The term "restoration" in context to the vintage car world has taken on a definition of its own. For some people, a restoration is simply painting a car and replacing items as needed, while for others, restoration means an extensive disassembly and overhaul, with each piece getting rebuilt or replaced.

As a consumer, it's important to understand the basics of restoration levels for it can impact classic car values substantially. There are hundreds of ways to “restore” a vintage car or truck including but not limited to the following: i). Frame off restoration. Body of vehicle is completely taken off the frame and restoration includes body, frame, floor pans (top and bottom), etc. these restorations tend to be extensive and costly. ii). Rotisserie restoration. These restorations are when the body (or body and frame on a unibody vehicle) are disassembled and restored utilizing a rotisserie. Body of vehicle is completely taken off the frame and restoration includes body, frame, floor pans (top and bottom), etc. these restorations tend to be extensive and costly and iii). Cosmetic or “driver quality” restoration. These restoration are typically limited to cosmetic items including paint and body, interior, trim and emblems, etc. Within the three levels or restoration mentioned above, there can be varying quality from an “in the garage / amateur” restoration to a high dollar professional “concours” restoration. There is a universal 100 point grading system rating classic car conditions ranging from 100 being excellent to 20 being unrestorable.

In addition to the levels of restoration above, it's important to understand the type of restoration as well for it can also impact value substantially. Type of restorations include: i). Factory or stock restoration. This type of restoration is geared towards restoring the car or truck to stock specs from the factory as if it were new. These types of restorations use original or oem (original equipment manufacturer) where possible. Factory original restorations tend to bring the highest dollars from collectors. ii). Custom restoration. These types of restorations are geared towards builder preference over factory stock. These can be refereed to as “customs” or “hot rods”. Typically these vehicles will have custom paint work, aftermarket wheels, suspension upgrades, power plant transplants, etc. A specific sector of custom restoration vehicles is “pro-touring” or “restomod / restomods” which are custom built with a more modern street performance and creature comforts than the original factory vehicle.
Please note that WWVA is not a restoration shop nor do we restore vehicles to any degree.

289ci V8 / Automatic

Exterior:
- Please see the video along with the listing, as the car is shown in detail. Every blemish on the car is shown close-up and in direct sunlight.

- Paint is a respray of what appears to be close to Gulfstream Aqua, a correct ‘68 Mustang color. Paint presents very well, with just a few very minor blemishes which are noted in the video. An A- from a cosmetic perspective.
- Glass and light lenses are all clear and crack-free.
- Black vinyl top is in excellent condition. One very small imperfection as shown in the video, but extremely nice overall.
- All chrome is like-new. Bumpers are fantastic, trim pieces are all in great shape as well.

- Polished wheels show no damage or oxidation. You may note one missing centercap in the photos, we have since installed one. Primewell Sport tires show little to no wear and the DOT number indicates they were manufactured in 2016.
Interior:

- Black vinyl interior is very nice. Seats show no signs of age or wear both front and rear. Impressive condition. The dash pad is not cracked, warped, or discolored either. The gauge cluster shows a bit of age by way of discoloring of the polished rings around the gauges.
- Gauges are all functional, including the odometer, which reads 24,252 miles. We are not positive of actual mileage, and have to assume the odometer has rolled over.
- Air conditioning is not functional. The compressor is there and is free, but air does not blow cold. Heat, fan, and defrost are functional. Radio is not functional.
- Black carpeting is nice throughout, with just a little bit of wear in the driver's footwell. The car will come with black Shelby floormats as well.
- Headliner is nice and tight.
Under the Hood / Underbody:

- Please take a look through the underbody photos, as it's documented in detail. Underbody is decent. No through structural rust or damage to note, but the car was undercoated years ago and that's flaking off now and doesn't look too pretty. Floors show nice clean black metal.

- This car is turn-key. A ready driver. It fires right up first turn, idles cool and steady, sounds fantastic (has a Thrush exhaust), pulls hard through the gears, shifts smoothly and without hesitation, and brakes well. It tracks straight both under acceleration and braking.
- This C-code car is powered by a 289ci 2V V8, as it should be, though we are not positive if it retains the original block or not.
